      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">BMI Limitations: Why It Does Not Work for Athletes</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 20, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>According to their BMI, many elite rugby players, bodybuilders, and professional athletes are "obese." This reveals a fundamental flaw in BMI as a health metric — it cannot tell the difference between muscle and fat. Here is what you should know.</p>

      <h2>The Core Problem</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">BMI = weight / height² (it ignores body composition entirely)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Muscle is denser than fat — muscular people weigh more at the same size</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Famous Examples</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson:</strong> BMI of ~34 (clinically "obese") at 6'5" and 118 kg of mostly muscle</li>
        <li><strong>Professional rugby players:</strong> Average BMI of 29-32 with very low body fat</li>
        <li><strong>Olympic sprinters:</strong> Often BMI 25-28 due to muscle mass</li>
        <li><strong>Strongman competitors:</strong> BMI 40+ while being extremely athletic</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who BMI Works Poorly For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Athletes and regular gym-goers</strong> with above-average muscle mass</li>
        <li><strong>Elderly people</strong> who lose muscle and gain fat — their BMI may stay "normal" while health declines</li>
        <li><strong>Very tall or very short people</strong> — BMI overestimates fatness in tall people and underestimates in short people</li>
        <li><strong>Different ethnic groups</strong> — health risks occur at different BMI thresholds for different populations</li>
        <li><strong>Pregnant women</strong> — BMI categories do not apply during pregnancy</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Better Alternatives</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Waist circumference:</strong> Risk increases above 94 cm (men) / 80 cm (women) — simple and effective</li>
        <li><strong>Waist-to-height ratio:</strong> Keep your waist less than half your height</li>
        <li><strong>Body fat percentage:</strong> Measured via DEXA scan, bioimpedance, or skinfold callipers</li>
        <li><strong>Waist-to-hip ratio:</strong> Another indicator of dangerous visceral fat</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolic markers:</strong> Blood pressure, blood sugar, cholesterol — direct health indicators</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>When BMI Is Still Useful</h2>
      <p>Despite its limitations, BMI remains valuable as:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A quick population-level screening tool (useful for public health research)</li>
        <li>A starting point for health conversations with your doctor</li>
        <li>A reasonable indicator for the average sedentary person</li>
        <li>A tracking metric when combined with other measurements over time</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The takeaway: if you exercise regularly and carry significant muscle mass, your BMI number may be meaningless. Focus instead on body fat percentage, waist circumference, and how you feel and perform.</p>

